"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167888","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-11-05","<p>There were no United Kingdom Government representatives on the final list of participants for the Second Global Rehabilitation 2030 Meeting in Geneva on 8 and 9 July 2019. A number of medical, academic and other representatives from the UK did however take part. The list of participants is attached due to the size of the data.</p>",,"Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford",,"2019-11-05T17:02:44.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167888/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167888/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167888/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-11-04","Rehabilitation: Conferences","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government which representatives attended the World Health Organisation Second Global Rehabilitation 2030 meeting in Geneva on 8 and 9 July.","false","Biography information for Lord Wigley",,"Lord Wigley","HL589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167792","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-11-05","<p>In September, under UK leadership, the five permanent members of the UN Security Council, plus Germany, Kuwait and Sweden, met and signed a communiqué reiterating the need to increase the pace and scale of the humanitarian response. The Group was clear that a political settlement is the only way to address the humanitarian crisis, but given the risk of starvation faced by millions in Yemen, the Group called on all donors to disburse promptly their pledges to the UN humanitarian response. It also called on the conflict parties to facilitate safe, rapid and unhindered humanitarian access in compliance with Security Council Resolution 2451. Our Permanent Representative to the UN also reiterated the need to bolster efforts on humanitarian access in her statement of 17 October to the UN Security Council.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-11-05T11:13:01.613Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167792/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167792/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167792/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-11-01","Yemen: International Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his UN counterparts on improving humanitarian access in Yemen.","false","Biography information for Jane Dodds","Brecon and Radnorshire","Jane Dodds","8612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167793","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-11-05","<p>The working day turnaround for Maternity Allowance claims averaged 55 working days up to the end of September 2019 and increased to 60 days by 15 October 2019.</p>","Eastleigh","Mims Davies",,"2019-11-05T16:43:11.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167793/answer","Biography information for Mims Davies","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167793/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167793/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-11-01","Maternity Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 31 October 2019 to Question 5404, what the working day turn around for maternity allowance claims was before 15 October 2019.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","8582"
