"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167649","Department for Education","false","2019-11-05","<p>Parents have a duty, under Section 7 of the Education Act 1996, to ensure that their child of compulsory school age (5-16) receives an efficient full-time education either by attendance at school or otherwise.</p><p>If parents register their child at school, the law places a duty on parents to ensure their child of compulsory school age attends school regularly.</p><p>A penalty notice is a fine issued to parents for failing to secure their child’s regular attendance at school. The Parental Responsibility Measures Attendance census collects data from local authorities annually on parental responsibility measures issued to address poor attendance in state-funded schools. It is a matter for schools and local authorities to decide whether to issue a penalty notice for unauthorised term time absence.</p><p>The Department has not formally assessed the impact of penalty notices, but comparable data shows overall absence rates have remained fairly stable across recent years, following a generally downward trend since 2006/07 (4.8% in 2017/18, compared to 6.5% in 2006/07).</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2019-11-05T16:50:53.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167649/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167649/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167649/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-10-31","Pupils: Truancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the (a) effect of the £60 fine per child or young person for unauthorised absences on the level of those absences and (b) potential effect of an increase in that fine on the level of absences.","false","Biography information for Eddie Hughes","Walsall North","Eddie Hughes","8268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167650","Department for Education","false","2019-11-05","<p>On 11 October 2019 we notified local authorities of their provisional allocations of high needs funding for the next financial year 2020-21, which included an additional £780 million, compared to their 2019-20 allocations. This additional £780 million will not be ring-fenced within the total high needs funding allocations to local authorities, which will rise to over £7 billion next year. The high needs allocations will form part of the dedicated schools grant to local authorities, and can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-funding-formula-tables-for-schools-and-high-needs-2020-to-2021" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/national-funding-formula-tables-for-schools-and-high-needs-2020-to-2021</a>.</p><p>The dedicated schools grant is ring-fenced and has to be spent by local authorities on education in accordance with the regulations and conditions of the grant.</p>","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan",,"2019-11-05T09:04:47.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167650/answer","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167650/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167650/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-10-31","Special Educational Needs: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, with reference to his Department's press release, Prime Minister boosts schools with £14 billion package, published on 30 August 2019, when the £700 million for children with special educational needs will be allocated; and whether that funding will be ring-fenced.","false","Biography information for Eddie Hughes","Walsall North","Eddie Hughes","8269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167651","Department for Education","false","2019-11-05","<p>The New Leaf Centre is a local authority maintained Pupil Referral Unit. Walsall local authority is responsible for the building project, so the department is unable to confirm timescales.</p><p> </p><p>Ofsted judged the school as inadequate following an inspection in April 2018. As a result, an Academy Order was issued by the Regional School’s Commissioner (RSC) on 28 June 2018. The Forward Education Trust were approved as sponsor of the school by the RSC in April 2019. The department is working closely with the local authority and the Forward Education Trust regarding the site issue.</p>","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan",,"2019-11-05T15:00:22.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167651/answer","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167651/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167651/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-10-31","Pupil Referral Units: Walsall","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the timescale is for the completion of the proposed rebuild project of New Leaf Pupil Referral Unit in Walsall.","false","Biography information for Eddie Hughes","Walsall North","Eddie Hughes","8270"
