"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167705","Department for Education","false","2019-11-05","<p>The department publishes figures on the number of independent schools and pupils attending them in the annual ‘Schools, Pupils and Characteristics’ release, by national totals and by local authority in tables 1a, 1b, and 1c, available here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2019" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/schools-pupils-and-their-characteristics-january-2019</a>.</p><p>The underlying data file includes figures for individual schools including school name, school type, parliamentary constituency and location. Full addresses can be found at the Get Information About Schools website, available here: <a href="https://get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/</a>.</p><p>The Oxford Analytics October 2018 report, 'The Impact of Independent Schools on the UK Economy' estimated that independent schools provide an annualised taxpayer cost saving of £3.5 billion, compared to the cost of educating all pupils in the state sector.</p>","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","8290 ; 8291","2019-11-05T14:22:23.42Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167705/answer","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167705/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167705/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-10-31","Private Education: Special Educational Needs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many independent special schools there are in each (a) local authority and (b) parliamentary constituency.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","8293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167706","Department for Education","false","2019-11-05","<p>Information about how many children from countries of the sixth enlargement of the EU who were enrolled in schools in the first (a) five and (b) 10 years after those countries joined the EU is only partially available (in an uncalculated format) and calculation of overall figures based even on partial data could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2019-11-05T16:35:46.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167706/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167706/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167706/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-10-31","Pupils: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many children from countries of the sixth enlargement of the EU were enrolled in schools in the first (a) five and (b) 10 years after those countries joined the EU; how many of those children were (i) primary school aged, (ii) secondary school aged and (iii) early years; and what the average cost to the public purse per child was in each of those settings since the sixth enlargement of the EU.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","8210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167707","Department for Education","false","2019-11-05","<p>Freedom of movement is already extended to Switzerland, Norway and Iceland.</p><p> </p><p>For Norway and Iceland, this is because they are members of the European Economic Area (EEA) and for Switzerland, this is because it is part of the single market.</p><p> </p><p>Regarding the other countries mentioned, no estimates have been made in relation to the possible scenario described.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2019-11-05T16:51:18.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167707/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167707/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167707/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-10-31","Schools: Admissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether he has made an estimate of the number of children enrolling in schools in England in the event of extending freedom of movement to nations including (a) Morocco, (b) Switzerland, (c) Norway, (d) Turkey, (e) North Macedonia, (f) Bosnia, (g) Serbia, (h) Kosovo, (i) Albania and (j) Iceland.","false","Biography information for Andrew Rosindell","Romford","Andrew Rosindell","8211"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167708","Cabinet Office","false","2019-11-05","<p>Protecting our children’s mental health is a priority for this Government, and a core part of the NHS Long Term Plan. The Government made available £1.4 billion to improve specialist children and young people’s mental health services between 2015-21.</p><p>The Government’s Green Paper on children and young people’s mental health recognises this is a cross-cutting issue which impacts on the work of multiple departments and arms-length bodies. It aims to improve the provision of mental health support so that children and young get the best possible start in life.</p><p>The proposals in the Green Paper have the potential to significantly improve early intervention and prevention by expanding the current children and young people’s mental health workforce and bolstering the capacity of schools and NHS services.</p><p>Given that the emotional and social development of children is a broad and complicated issue, the responsibility for the area sits across multiple departments including the Department for Health and Social Care, The Department for Education, the Department of Work and Pensions, and the Department for Housing Communities and Local Government.</p><p> </p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden",,"2019-11-05T11:57:55.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167708/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167708/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167708/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-10-31","Mental Health: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster and Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps the Government is taking to develop a cross-departmental approach to promoting young people’s mental health; what assessment he has made of cross-departmental responsibilities for promoting young people’s mental health; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","8250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167709","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-11-05","<p>We are providing around £600 million of funding for the remediation of unsafe Aluminium Composite Material (ACM) cladding in high rise residential buildings in the social and private sector. We are pushing owners and local authorities hard to remediate unsafe buildings and we expect to see building owners take action. We have so far allocated £259 million to replace cladding on 140 social sector buildings. In the private sector we expect all eligible buildings to have applied to the fund by the end of this year. We will continue to maintain pressure on developers and building owners to do the right thing and get on with remediation. We will set out progress on remediation in the next data release on 14 November.</p>","Tatton","Esther McVey",,"2019-11-05T14:30:29.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167709/answer","Biography information for Esther McVey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167709/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167709/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-10-31","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, how many payments have been made from the Government's fund for the removal and replacement of unsafe cladding; who those payments have been made to; what criteria has been applied to allocate that funding; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dame Louise Ellman","Liverpool, Riverside","Dame Louise Ellman","8212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167710","Department for Education","false","2019-11-05","<p>The System Partnerships Unit (SPU) works across several policy and regional delivery teams within the Department. There are two central SPU staff members, within Departmental policy teams, at Grade 7 and SEO, although they also have other non-SPU related duties. In order to protect individuals’ personal information, the Department can not disclose information on educational background.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to the central staff, there are delivery leads in each of the eight Regional School Commissioner (RSC) regions who have a wide range of school improvement duties, of which supporting partnerships is one part. As such, they are employed by the RSCs rather than as part of a central unit.</p>","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","8295 ; 8296","2019-11-05T14:47:39.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167710/answer","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167710/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167710/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-10-31","Private Education: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 14 October 2019 to Question 284 on Private Education: West Midlands, how many people are employed by the unit on promoting cross-sector partnerships (a) in total and (b) at each civil service grade.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","8294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167711","Department for Education","false","2019-11-05","<p>The System Partnerships Unit (SPU) works across several policy and regional delivery teams within the Department. There are two central SPU staff members, within Departmental policy teams, at Grade 7 and SEO, although they also have other non-SPU related duties. In order to protect individuals’ personal information, the Department can not disclose information on educational background.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to the central staff, there are delivery leads in each of the eight Regional School Commissioner (RSC) regions who have a wide range of school improvement duties, of which supporting partnerships is one part. As such, they are employed by the RSCs rather than as part of a central unit.</p>","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","8294 ; 8296","2019-11-05T14:47:39.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167711/answer","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167711/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167711/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-10-31","Private Education: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 14 October 2019 to Question 284 on Private Education: West Midlands, how many people employed by the unit on promoting cross-sector partnerships attended (a) an independent secondary school and (b) a state secondary school.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","8295"
