"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167713","Department for Education","false","2019-11-05","<p>The total planned value of the cross-sector partnerships grant is £219,500.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is currently inviting bids and schools have been asked to submit proposals by 3pm on 29 November 2019.</p><p> </p><p>As the bidding window is still open, the Department is unable to publish the number or type of applications received. Future decisions about the award of the grant will be taken by ministers post-election.</p><p> </p>","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","8298","2019-11-05T15:19:23.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167713/answer","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167713/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167713/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-10-31","Private Education: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 22 October 2019 Question 284 on Private Education: West Midlands, what the value is of the cross-sector partnerships grant.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","8297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167714","Department for Education","false","2019-11-05","<p>The total planned value of the cross-sector partnerships grant is £219,500.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is currently inviting bids and schools have been asked to submit proposals by 3pm on 29 November 2019.</p><p> </p><p>As the bidding window is still open, the Department is unable to publish the number or type of applications received. Future decisions about the award of the grant will be taken by ministers post-election.</p><p> </p>","Chippenham","Michelle Donelan","8297","2019-11-05T15:19:23.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167714/answer","Biography information for Michelle Donelan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167714/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167714/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-10-31","Private Education: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 14 October 2019 to Question 284 on Private Education: West Midlands, how many applications for the cross-sector partnerships grant there have been for (a) independent school-non-selective state school partnerships and (b) independent school-selective state school partnerships.","false","Biography information for Preet Kaur Gill","Birmingham, Edgbaston","Preet Kaur Gill","8298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167715","Department for Transport","false","2019-11-05","<p>For the Main Access for All programme, we received nominations for more than 300 stations, including Ledbury, and in April we announced the 73 stations that would benefit from the funding. Unfortunately Ledbury was not selected as its comparatively low passenger usage made it difficult to justify its inclusion ahead of other busier stations in the region.</p><p> </p><p>For the Mid-Tier Access for All programme, nominations were required by 18 October but there was no nomination for Ledbury station.</p><p> </p><p>However, the Inclusive Transport Strategy sets out what we are doing to improve access across all transport modes, and we will continue to seek further opportunities, and funding, to make more improvements.</p><p> </p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2019-11-05T11:54:34.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167715/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167715/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167715/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-10-31","Ledbury Station: Access","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress he has made in assessing the merits of allocating Access for All funding for the purposes of making Ledbury Station step-free.","false","Biography information for Bill Wiggin","North Herefordshire","Bill Wiggin","8213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167716","Leader of the House","false","2019-11-05","<p>The way in which individual Members of Parliament fulfill their responsibilities in Parliament is a matter for them, rather than the Government. There are established party processes in place for when a member is absent, such as pairing.</p><p> </p>","North East Somerset","Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg",,"2019-11-05T17:46:05.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167716/answer","Biography information for Mr Jacob Rees-Mogg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167716/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167716/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2019-10-31","Members: Juries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, what steps he has taken to establish a mechanism by which the Government takes responsibility for MPs' absence for jury service.","false","Biography information for Bill Wiggin","North Herefordshire","Bill Wiggin","8214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167717","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-11-05","<p>We are not aware of Mr Hyon Hak Bong's current role and have not taken steps to locate him.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2019-11-05T15:14:16.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167717/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167717/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167717/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-31","Hyon Hak-Bong","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government has taken to locate the  former North Korean Ambassador to the United Kingdom Hak Byong Hyon.","false","Biography information for Bill Wiggin","North Herefordshire","Bill Wiggin","8215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167718","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2019-11-05","<p>The Government’s awarding of Growth Deal 3 funding in March 2017 provided a boost of £21.9 million for the Marches area.</p><p> </p><p>Since the Deal was agreed, the Marches Local Enterprise Partnership (LEP) have been working closely with the New Model in Technology and Engineering (NMiTE) project. The LEP also provided development funding to the project to support the completion of the business case.</p><p> </p><p>A location for the first phase of development has been identified. The LEP have recently received a business case for the second phase of development, and discussions aimed at agreeing the next tranche of funding are ongoing.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2019-11-05T16:51:50.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167718/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167718/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167718/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2019-10-31","Universities: Herefordshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps the Marches local enterprise partnership has taken to support the New Model in Technology and Engineering university project in Herefordshire.","false","Biography information for Bill Wiggin","North Herefordshire","Bill Wiggin","8216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167719","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-11-05","<p>The award of Growth Deal 3 funding was announced in March 2017 providing a boost of £21.9 million for the Marches area, aimed at helping to create jobs, support businesses and encourage growth. This tranche of funding was expected to deliver a number of projects, which included proposals to provide capital support to the <em>New Model in Technology and Engineering </em>(NMiTE) University project in Herefordshire.</p><p>Since the deal was agreed, the Marches Local Enterprise Partnerships (LEP) have been working with the NMiTE project to refine their proposal, further develop their business case, and engage with wider stakeholders. The LEP also provided development funding to the project to support the completion of the business case.</p><p>In October 2017, the Department for Education announced a further £15 million to support development of the faculty, campus and curriculum. Following this agreement, the NMITE project were able to develop their proposal further and in Autumn of 2018 a location for the first phase of development was identified.</p><p>This was followed in October 2019 by LEP confirmation of £2.34 million investment to fund the transformation of a former school into facilities for Hereford’s proposed new university.</p><p>The LEP continue to work with the NMiTE project as a member of their board and governance structure. The LEP have recently received a business case for the second phase of development, and discussions aimed at agreeing the next tranche of funding are ongoing.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","8218","2019-11-05T11:35:41.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167719/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167719/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167719/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-10-31","Universities: Herefordshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, for what reasons the Marches LEP released Phase 1 funding for the New Model in Technology and Engineering university project in Herefordshire in August 2019 given that Local Growth Fund 3 was announced in March 2017.","false","Biography information for Bill Wiggin","North Herefordshire","Bill Wiggin","8217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167720","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-11-05","<p>The award of Growth Deal 3 funding was announced in March 2017 providing a boost of £21.9 million for the Marches area, aimed at helping to create jobs, support businesses and encourage growth. This tranche of funding was expected to deliver a number of projects, which included proposals to provide capital support to the <em>New Model in Technology and Engineering </em>(NMiTE) University project in Herefordshire.</p><p>Since the deal was agreed, the Marches Local Enterprise Partnerships (LEP) have been working with the NMiTE project to refine their proposal, further develop their business case, and engage with wider stakeholders. The LEP also provided development funding to the project to support the completion of the business case.</p><p>In October 2017, the Department for Education announced a further £15 million to support development of the faculty, campus and curriculum. Following this agreement, the NMITE project were able to develop their proposal further and in Autumn of 2018 a location for the first phase of development was identified.</p><p>This was followed in October 2019 by LEP confirmation of £2.34 million investment to fund the transformation of a former school into facilities for Hereford’s proposed new university.</p><p>The LEP continue to work with the NMiTE project as a member of their board and governance structure. The LEP have recently received a business case for the second phase of development, and discussions aimed at agreeing the next tranche of funding are ongoing.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry","8217","2019-11-05T11:35:41.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167720/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167720/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167720/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-10-31","Universities: Herefordshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, when the Marches LEP plans to release the £5.7 million of Phase 2 funding allocated by the Government for the New Model in Technology and Engineering university project in Herefordshire.","false","Biography information for Bill Wiggin","North Herefordshire","Bill Wiggin","8218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167721","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-11-05","<p>It has not proved possible to respond to the hon. Member in the time available before Dissolution.</p>","Plymouth, Moor View","Johnny Mercer",,"2019-11-05T11:49:06.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167721/answer","Biography information for Johnny Mercer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167721/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167721/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-10-31","National Rifle Association","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the National Rifle Association's compliance with its charitable purpose to promote the (a) efficiency of the armed forces and (b) defence of the Realm.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","8190"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167722","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-11-05","<p>I have held no meetings with representatives of the Charity Commission to discuss the corporate governance standards of the National Rifle Association.</p>","Loughborough","Nicky Morgan",,"2019-11-05T13:53:36.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167722/answer","Biography information for Nicky Morgan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167722/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167722/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-10-31","National Rifle Association","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, whether she has held meetings with representatives of the Charity Commission to discuss the corporate governance standards of the National Rifle Association.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","8194"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167732","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2019-11-05","<p><em>It has not proved possible to respond to this question in the time available before Dissolution. Ministers will correspond directly with the Member.</em></p><p> </p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2019-11-05T16:58:22.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167732/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167732/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167732/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2019-10-31","European Economic Area and European Free Trade Association","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 17 January (HL12669) and  the Written Statement by Lord Callanan on 20 December 2018 (HLWS1187), whether (1) the text of the EEA EFTA Separation Agreement has been amended since 20 December 2018, and (2) the EEA EFTA Separation Agreement has been signed by the UK; if so, when; whether the EEA EFTA Separation Agreement is subject to section 20 of the Constitutional Reform and Governance Act 2010; and whether a copy of the EEA EFTA Separation Agreement has been laid before Parliament by a Minister of the Crown within the meaning of section 20(1)(a) of the Constitutional Reform and Governance Act 2010.","false","Biography information for Lord Anderson of Ipswich",,"Lord Anderson of Ipswich","HL572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167733","Home Office","false","2019-11-05","<p>The actions of French police and security personnel remain the domestic responsibility of the French government, and as such the UK is unable to comment on their actions. Those who are moved on from camps are provided with the option of transport to asylum centres where their claims can be lodged and considered expediently. Within these centres, individuals are provided with any medical and administrative support they require. The Sandhurst Treaty and associated funding has supported this work. The UK and France will continue to collaborate in response to this issue, ensuring that the necessary support is delivered whilst upholding border security at our shared border.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2019-11-05T17:46:05.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167733/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167733/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167733/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-31","Refugees: France","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the government of France about police brutality towards refugees in Northern France, in particular about any incidents on 24 October near Calais; and whether such behaviour is consistent with the Sandhurst Agreement.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167734","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-11-05","<p>We are in regular dialogue with relevant NGOs on a range of migration issues. We have routine discussions of Search and Rescue and the situation of migrants in Libya with Médecins sans frontières.</p><p>We remain committed to supporting Greece's efforts to manage migration effectively. We are working with the Greek Government, who retain responsibility for the situation of migrants in the country, to this end. United Kingdom vessels have rescued 16,000 migrants in the Aegean since 2015.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-11-05T17:26:12.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167734/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167734/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167734/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-31","Europe: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when they last had discussions with UNICEF and Médecins Sans Frontières about (1) the refugees on the Greek Islands, (2) rescues from the Mediterranean, including children aged 5 to 17, and (3) unaccompanied minors who have reached France.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167735","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2019-11-05","<p>The commemorations for the 400th Mayflower anniversary are being organised by a partnership of organisations called the Mayflower 400, who are ultimately responsible for organising and delivering the commemorations.</p><p> </p><p>UK Government, primarily through the Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS), has provided some financial support to the Mayflower 400’s programme. This is demonstrated by the £750,000 funding that DCMS has provided through VisitEngland, which will help to ensure a strong legacy for the commemorations. In 2015, DCMS provided £35,000 to invest in the Mayflower museum and in 2019, DCMS awarded £3.5m through the Cultural Development Fund for digital product development.</p>",,"Baroness Barran",,"2019-11-05T13:59:21.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167735/answer","Biography information for Baroness Barran","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167735/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167735/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2019-10-31","Mayflower: Anniversaries","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government which (1) Department, and (2) ministers, are responsible for organising the 400th anniversary of the sailing of the Mayflower.","false","Biography information for Earl Attlee",,"Earl Attlee","HL575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167736","Home Office","false","2019-11-05","<p><em>The Home Office does not record the information in such a way that allows us to report on what percentage of people seeking asylum in the UK are doing so because they are fleeing domestic violence.</em></p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2019-11-05T17:40:35.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167736/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167736/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167736/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-31","Asylum: Domestic Abuse","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what percentage of people seeking asylum in the UK are doing so because they are fleeing domestic violence.","false","Biography information for Lord Sheikh",,"Lord Sheikh","HL576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167737","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-11-05","<p>In the Agriculture Bill introduced in the previous session, broadly similar powers were conferred on the Welsh Ministers as on the Secretary of State for England. This was done at the request of the Welsh Ministers and included the powers in clause 11. This means that the Welsh Ministers would have powers to modify retained EU legislation relating to the financing, management and monitoring of Common Agricultural Policy schemes.</p><p> </p><p>The Welsh Government have also announced that they will bring forward their own Agriculture Bill in the National Assembly at a later date. The Welsh Government have informed me that this will be preceded by a White Paper, intended to be brought forward during the current Assembly term.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2019-11-05T17:11:10.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167737/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167737/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167737/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-10-31","Agriculture: Subsidies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the remarks by Lord Morris of Aberavon on 17 October (HL Deb, col 198), when they will be in a position to reply to the issues raised about agricultural support after Brexit, particularly in relation to Wales.","false","Biography information for Lord Morris of Aberavon",,"Lord Morris of Aberavon","HL577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167294","Northern Ireland Office","false","2019-10-30","<p>I was disappointed that the parties were unable to reach an accommodation before the 21 October deadline. Getting Stormont back up and running remains my absolute priority, and I will do everything in my power to make it happen before the 13 January deadline. At that point, the choices facing us will be very limited indeed.</p>","Skipton and Ripon","Julian Smith",,"2019-10-30T15:08:18.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167294/answer","Biography information for Julian Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167294/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167294/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2019-10-30","Devolution: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","What progress has been made on restoring devolved government in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Bob Blackman","Harrow East","Bob Blackman","900152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167295","Northern Ireland Office","false","2019-10-30","<p>I have regular discussions with the Irish Government concerning the UK's exit from the EU.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is fully committed to ensuring there will be no hard border between Northern Ireland and Ireland. The Prime Minister has negotiated a new deal which ensures that will be the case.</p>","Skipton and Ripon","Julian Smith",,"2019-10-30T15:09:26.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167295/answer","Biography information for Julian Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167295/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167295/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2019-10-30","Borders: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","What recent discussions he has had with the Irish Government on ensuring that there is no hard border on the island of Ireland.","false","Biography information for Greg Hands","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","900154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167296","Northern Ireland Office","false","2019-10-30","<p>Northern Ireland continues to benefit from the decision taken by this Government to build a stronger economy across the whole of the United Kingdom. Of particular importance, is the Tech Sector, which provides highly skilled and rewarding jobs, as well as boosting innovation.</p><p>The UK Government has announced economic investments of over £600m through City and Growth Deals and other initiatives that cover all 11 councils in Northern Ireland. This provides an excellent opportunity for each to enrich their Tech Sector capabilities, including digital and R&amp;D innovations; and clearly demonstrates the Government’s continued support for the development of skills provision and growth in this innovative sector.</p>","Skipton and Ripon","Julian Smith",,"2019-10-30T15:11:09.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167296/answer","Biography information for Julian Smith","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167296/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167296/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2019-10-30","Technology: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","What recent assessment he has made of the economic importance of the tech sector to Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Chris Green","Bolton West","Chris Green","900156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167344","Department for Transport","false","2019-11-04","<p>The department procures data and analysis from external consultants, which allows us to assess current and potential future capital costs, running costs, and the whole life cost or ‘Total Cost of Ownership’ (TCO) for different categories of electric, diesel and petrol vehicles. We monitor for similar analysis produced by external parties to verify our understanding of how TCO, and the economic case for owning an ultra-low emission vehicle (ULEV), is expected to evolve over time. When deemed necessary, we commission updates or revisions to the data and analysis. At the moment the Department does not conduct this analysis for individual consumer groups.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2019-11-04T14:50:11.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167344/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167344/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167344/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-10-30","Electric Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what (a) monitoring and (b) analysis his Department undertakes of the average (i) capital cost, (ii) running cost and (iii) whole-life cost of electric vehicles relative to (A) petrol and (B) diesel vehicles for different (1) categories of vehicle and (2) groups of users.","false","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","East Hampshire","Mr Damian Hinds","7800"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167345","Treasury","false","2019-11-04","<p>The Government takes Authorised Push Payment (APP) fraud extremely seriously. Victims and their families can suffer both serious financial and emotional harm and it is right that industry takes the necessary steps to protect consumers.</p><p> </p><p>The Payment Systems Regulator, which was set up by the Government in 2015, established a steering group to develop a voluntary industry Code of good practice that set the circumstances in which customers will be reimbursed if they fall victim to these kinds of scam. The Code became effective on 28 May 2019.</p><p> </p><p>Pay.UK, under whom the Faster Payments Scheme sits, have consulted on the Change Request, which would introduce a levy on Faster Payments transactions for the reimbursement of victims in the long-term. The final decision sits with Pay.UK and it would not be appropriate for the Government to comment on the specifics of this proposal.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2019-11-04T14:06:36.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167345/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167345/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167345/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-10-30","Electronic Funds Transfer: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential benefits of the UK Finance proposal for a Faster Payment Scheme Change Request to provide a long-term sustainable funding system for reimbursing of victims of authorised push payment fraud.","false","Biography information for Chris Elmore","Ogmore","Chris Elmore","7748"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167346","Home Office","false","2019-11-05","<p>The Home Office processes honours nominations for Home Office employees and our stakeholders, including members of the Fire and Rescue Service and the Police Service. The information requested is provided the attached table.</p><p> </p>","Louth and Horncastle","Victoria Atkins",,"2019-11-05T15:38:48.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167346/answer","Biography information for Victoria Atkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167346/answer","Copy of Table A_PQ 7685_311019.xls","Table A - PQ 7685","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167346/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-10-30","Home Office: Honours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of staff in his Department in receipt of each category of Honour in (a) December 2018 and (b) June 2019 were (i) from ethnic minority backgrounds and (ii) female aged (A) under 30 (B) 31 to 40 (C) 41 to 50 and (D) aged over 50.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","7685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167347","Cabinet Office","false","2019-11-04","<p>In 2017, the Government introduced world-leading legislation that made it statutory for organisations with 250 or more employees to report annually on their gender pay gap. Government departments are covered by the Equality Act 2010 (Specific Duties and Public Authorities) Regulations 2017 which came into force on 31 March 2017. These regulations underpin the Public Sector Equality Duty and require the relevant organisations to publish their gender pay gap data by 30 March annually.</p><p>Each year, in addition to reporting the figures required by the legislation each department publishes a stand alone report outlining the reasons that contribute to their gender pay gap and the action plans aimed at reducing it. At present there is no set date by which gender pay gaps will be eliminated and it is acknowledged that it will take many years.</p><p>Individual departmental gender pay gap reports are available on gov.uk.</p><p> </p>","Carmarthen West and South Pembrokeshire","Simon Hart",,"2019-11-04T10:27:05.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167347/answer","Biography information for Simon Hart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167347/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167347/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-10-30","Government Departments: Equal Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster and Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether each Department has set a target for the elimination of the gender pay gap in their workforce; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","7686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167348","Department for International Development","false","2019-11-04","<p>Gavi’s mission to save children’s lives by increasing equitable use of vaccines is directly aligned to the UK’s ambition to end preventable deaths of new-born babies and children under 5 years of age by 2030, under Sustainable Development Goal 3, and we have recently renewed our commitment to this goal. The UK is the largest donor to Gavi, the Vaccine Alliance, committing £1.44 billion between 2016 and 2020. This support will vaccinate 76 million additional children by 2020, saving 1.4 million lives from vaccine-preventable diseases in 68 of the world’s poorest countries. The UK will host the pledging conference for Gavi in June 2020.</p><p>DFID support to Gavi includes a wider package of health care support designed to strengthen and integrate services. Immunisation is often a child’s first point of contact with their health service. It creates an opportunity where malnourished children can be identified and treated. Vaccines can also prevent some of the infectious diseases and causes of malnutrition.</p><p>The UK is committed to investment in the integration of nutrition within other sectors, including health. We have championed efforts to achieve universal health coverage by bringing together initiatives on health security, antimicrobial resistance, and nutrition, into a single universal health coverage approach.</p>","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison",,"2019-11-04T17:32:30.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167348/answer","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167348/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167348/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2019-10-30","Gavi, the Vaccine Alliance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, if the Government will ensure that its support for the Vaccine Alliance, Gavi, in 2020 will include the objective of improving nutrition for children under the age of five.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","7653"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167349","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-11-04","<p>The United Kingdom remains committed to working closely with the government of Ukraine, our international partners and local agencies to support efforts to report, investigate and reduce incidences of hate crime.</p>","Tamworth","Christopher Pincher",,"2019-11-04T17:43:36.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167349/answer","Biography information for Christopher Pincher","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167349/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167349/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-10-30","Ukraine: Hate Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of trends in the level of hate crime investigations in Ukraine; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Fabian Hamilton","Leeds North East","Fabian Hamilton","7637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167350","Treasury","false","2019-11-04","<p>The Treasury sets the Northern Ireland administration’s overall Financial Transaction Capital budget through the normal operation of the Barnett formula.</p><p> </p><p>The allocation and use of Financial Transactions Capital is a devolved function and a matter for the Northern Ireland administration. This includes determining Northern Ireland departmental budget profiles and providing support for applicants for Financial Transactions Capital funding.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak","7688","2019-11-04T10:27:40.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167350/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167350/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167350/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-10-30","Public Expenditure: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what (a) practical, (b) financial and (c) other support Northern Ireland Government Departments have provided to applicants in preparing their applications, designs, cost planning, option appraisals, business cases and green book appraisals for Financial Transactions Capital funding.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","7687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167351","Treasury","false","2019-11-04","<p>The Treasury sets the Northern Ireland administration’s overall Financial Transaction Capital budget through the normal operation of the Barnett formula.</p><p> </p><p>The allocation and use of Financial Transactions Capital is a devolved function and a matter for the Northern Ireland administration. This includes determining Northern Ireland departmental budget profiles and providing support for applicants for Financial Transactions Capital funding.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak","7687","2019-11-04T10:27:40.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167351/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167351/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1167351/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2019-10-30","Public Expenditure: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the profiled budgets are for Financial Transactions Capital funding in each Northern Ireland Government Department in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","7688"
